ge/n180 135]|year=2007|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=0-300-12078-8| ref = {{sfnRef|Khan|2007}}}}\n*{{cite book|author=Bina D Costa|title=Nationbuilding, Gender and War Crimes in South Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ivzKjY5LncIC&pg=PA102|year=2010|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415565660| ref = {{sfnRef|D'Costa|2010}}}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Ritu Menon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yNN4SE7cL60C&pg=PA70|title=Borders & Boundaries: Women in India's Partition|author2=Kamla Bhasin|publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=1998|isbn=978-0-8135-2552-5| ref = {{sfnRef|Menon|1998}}}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Major |first1=Andrew |title=Abduction of women during the partition of the Punjab |journal=South Asia: Journal of South Asian Studies |date=1995 |volume=18 |issue=1 |doi=10.1080/00856409508723244| ref = {{sfnRef|Major|1995}}}}\n*{{cite book|author=Amal Kumar Chattopadhyay|title=Slavery in India; with an introduction by Radha Kumud Mukherjee and with a foreword by Asim Kumar Datta|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.105457/page/n165/mode/2up|year=1959|publisher=Nagarjun Press|ref={{sfnRef|Chattopadhyay|1959}}}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Jacqueline Suthren Hirst|author2=John Zavos|title=Religious Traditions in Modern South Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bBOpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA152|date=March 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-62668-5| ref = {{sfnRef|Hirst|2013}}}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Gyanendra Pandey|author2=Professor of History Gyanendra Pandey|title=Remembering Partition: Violence, Nationalism and History in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZdLhnFet4w4C&pg=PA165|date=22 November 2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-00250-9|ref = {{sfnRef|Pandey|2001}}}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Barbara D. Metcalf|author2=Thomas R. Metcalf|title=A Concise History of Modern India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c7UgAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA226|date=24 September 2012|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-53705-6| ref = {{sfnRef|Metcalf|2012}}}}\n*{{cite journal |title= Islam's Black Slaves: The Other Black Diaspora by Ronald Segal- Book Review |journal=The Journal of Blacks in Higher Education |date=2001 |number=31 | ref = {{sfnRef|Islam's Black Slaves|2001}}}}\n*{{cite book|author=Jok Madut Jok|title=War and Slavery in Sudan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wqzvlWdxThwC|date=3 August 2010|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=0-8122-0058-6| ref ={{sfnRef|Jok|2010}}}}\n*{{cite book|author=N. Nojumi|title=The Rise of the Taliban in Afghanistan: Mass Mobilization, Civil War, and the Future of the Region|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h18YDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA168|date=30 April 2016|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan US|isbn=978-0-312-29910-1| ref = {{sfnRef|Nojumi|2016}}}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Peter J. Claus|author2=Sarah Diamond|author3=Margaret Ann Mills|title=South Asian Folklore: An Encyclopedia : Afghanistan, Bangladesh, India, Nepal, Pakistan, Sri Lanka|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ienxrTPHzzwC&pg=PA7|year=2003|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-93919-5| ref = {{sfnRef|Claus|2003}}}}\n*{{cite book|author=Jacqueline L. Hazelton|title=Beyond Slavery: Overcoming Its Religious and Sexual Legacies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NaVhAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT3|date=25 October 2010|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-0-230-11389-3| ref = {{sfnRef|Hazelton|2010}}}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Ali |first1=Kecia |title=Redeeming Slavery: The \u2018Islamic State\u2019 and the Quest for Islamic Morality |journal=Mizan: Journal for the Study of Muslim Societies and Civilizations |date=2016 |volume=1 |issue=1  |url=https://mizanproject.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/02-Mizan-Journal-Vol-1_Issue-1_Ali_Redeeming-Slavery.pdf| ref = {{sfnRef|Ali|2016}}}}\n*{{cite book|author1=William Gervase Clarence-Smith|author2=W. G. Clarence-Smith|title=Islam and the Abolition of Slavery|url=https://archive.org/details/islamabolitionof0000clar|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/islamabolitionof0000clar/page/n56 27]|year=2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-522151-0| ref = {{sfnRef|Smith|2006}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Groups practising sexual slavery]]\n[[Category:Concubinage]]\n[[Category:Wartime sexual violence]]\n[[Category:Violence against women]]\n[[Category:Slavery]]\n", "name_user": "Mcphurphy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sexual_slavery_in_Islam"}
{"title_page": "Warwick Allerton - Chicago", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Allerton Hotel|the New York City Hotel|Allerton Hotel for Women}}\n{{Use American English|date = November 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox building\n|name               = Warwick Allerton - Chicago\n|image              = 20070513_Allerton_Hotel_and_Michigan_Ave_edit_cropped.jpg\n|image_size         = 300px\n|location           = 701 North [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]].<br/>[[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n|caption            = \n|coordinates        = {{coord|41.8952|-87.6238|region:US-IL|display=inline,title}}\n|status             = \n|start_date         = 1922\n|completion_date    = 1924\n|opening            = 1924\n|building_type      = hotel\n|antenna_spire      = \n|roof               = {{convert|360|ft|m}}\n|top_floor          = \n|floor_count        = 25\n|elevator_count     = \n|cost               = $4 million\n|floor_area         = \n|architect          = Murgatroyd & Ogden, with [[Fugard & Knapp]]\n|structural_engineer= \n|main_contractor    = \n|developer          = Allerton Hotels\n|owner              = [[Warwick International Hotels (WIH)|Warwick International Hotels]]\n|embedded           = {{Designation list|embed=yes|designation1=Chicago|designation1_date=May 29, 1998}}\n|references         = <ref>{{emporis|116862}}</ref>\n}}\n[[File:Allerton Tip Top Tap sign (15578891745).jpg|thumb|right|200px|'Tip Top Tap' sign]]\nThe '''Warwick Allerton - Chicago''' (formerly '''Allerton Hotel''' and '''Warwick Allerton Hotel Chicago''' and '''Allerton Crowne Plaza Hotel''') is a 25-story {{convert|360|ft|m|abbr=on}} hotel skyscraper on the [[Magnificent Mile]] in the [[Near North Side, Chicago|Near North Side]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]].<ref name=EMP>{{cite web| url=http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=allertoncrowneplaza-chicago-il-usa|accessdate=May 14, 2007| year=2007| title=Allerton Crowne Plaza| publisher=Emporis| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070429025629/http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=allertoncrowneplaza-chicago-il-usa| archivedate= April 29, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>   It was the first building in the city to feature pronounced setbacks and towers resulting from the 1923 zoning law.<ref name=\"EMP\" /><ref name=\"trib1\">{{cite press release| title=Chicago's Historic Allerton Hotel Rechristened an Independent Property| publisher=Oxford Lodging | date=February 5, 2007| accessdate=August 28, 2015| url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Chicago%27s+Historic+Allerton+Hotel+Rechristened+an+Independent...-a0158830052}}</ref> The building was designated a [[Chicago Landmark]] on May 29, 1998.<ref name=CL>{{cite web| url=http://webapps.cityofchicago.org/landmarksweb/web/landmarkdetails.htm?lanId=1237| title=Allerton Hotel| publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division| year=2003| accessdate=May 14, 2007}}</ref>\n\nWhen the Allerton Hotel first opened, it had fourteen floors of small apartment-style rooms for men and six similar floors for women, with a total of 1,000 rooms.  The hotel also boasted social events, gold, sports leagues, a library, solarium, and an in-house magazine.<ref name=\"trib2\">{{cite news| last=Conklin| first=Mike| title=75 Years Later, Allerton's Again in Tip Top Shape| work=[[Chicago Tribune]]| url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-05-21/features/9905210219_1_tap-new-owners-new-buildings| date=May 21, 1999}}</ref> An early resident was [[Louis Skidmore]], founder of the architectural firm [[Skidmore, Owings & Merrill]].\n\nIn the 1940s and 1950s, the hotel housed a swanky lounge on its top floor, called the \"Tip Top Tap\".  Although the lounge closed in 1961, the sign proclaiming its existence is still displayed on the building's exterior.<ref name=\"trib1\"/> By 1963, the room was home to a new restaurant, the Cloud Room, when [[Don McNeill (performer)|Don McNeill]] moved his broadcast of ''[[Don McNeill's Breakfast Club]]'' to the location. While the show was broadcast from the Allerton, McNeill's guests included regular [[Fran Allison]].<ref name=\"trib2\"/>\n\nAfter the Allerton Hotel was declared a Chicago landmark, it closed in August 1998 through May 1999 for a $40 million renovation.<ref name=\"trib2\" /><ref name=schmeltzer>{{cite news| title=Landmark Allerton Gets A Crowne| url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-03-26/business/9903260216_1_bass-hotels-resorts-historic-hotel-hotel-arm| last=Schmeltzer| first=John| date=March 26, 1999| work=Chicago Tribune| accessdate=August 28, 2015}}</ref> The firm of Eckenhoff Saunders Architects oversaw restoration work which restored the hotel's bygone grandeur and upgraded mechanical systems.<ref name=esa>{{cite web| title=Allerton Crowne Plaza Hotel| url=http://www.esadesign.com/portfolio/allerton/| publisher=Eckenhoff Saunders Architects| accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref>  When the hotel reopened as the Allerton Crowne Plaza Hotel, the twenty-third floor, which previously housed the Tip Top Tap and the Cloud Room, became the Renaissance Ballroom and a lounge opened on the second floor called Taps on Two featuring one of the Tip Top Tap's signature drinks, a [[Moscow mule]].<ref name=\"trib2\" />\n\nIn November 2006, a partnership of Oxford Lodging and Perry Capital purchased the hotel from FelCor Lodging for $70 million.<ref name=roeder>{{cite news| title=Allerton to get $10 mil. face-lift| url=http://charterslodging.com/PR_Articles/ChicagoSunTimes_Allerton.pdf| last=Roeder| first=David| work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]| date=November 10, 2006| accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref> The new owners ended the affiliation with Crowne Plaza and on February 2, 2007, the property was re-christened ''The Allerton Hotel''.  Shortly after the purchase, Oxford announced further renovations to the property.<ref name=\"trib1\"/>\n\nIn March 2014, [[Warwick International Hotels (WIH)|Warwick International Hotels]], a New York-based hotel chain, purchased the Allerton and renamed it the \"Warwick Allerton Hotel\".  Warwick acquired the Allerton from New York-based hedge fund manager Petra Capital Management LLC, which won a 2012-battle for control of the property in bankruptcy court.<ref name=diamond>{{cite press release| title=DiamondRock Hospitality Reaches Settlement on the Bankruptcy and Litigation Surrounding the Allerton Hotel in Chicago| url=http://www.hotel-online.com/News/PR2012_4th/Oct12_DiamondRockAllerton.html| date=October 31, 2012| accessdate=May 12, 2014| publisher=DiamondRock Hospitality}}</ref>  The new owners are planning renovations which may include reopening the Tip Top Tap on the hotel's 23rd floor.<ref name=hirst>{{cite news| url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-03-25/business/ct-chicago-hotels-allerton-0325-biz-20140325_1_hotel-rooms-radio-station-hotel-closing| title=New Allerton Hotel owner may return Tip Top Tap to its high point| accessdate=May 12, 2014| date=March 25, 2014| last=Hirst| first=Jean Ellen| work=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commons category-inline|The Allerton Hotel Chicago}}\n* [http://warwickhotels.com/allerton-hotel-chicago Warwick Allerton Hotel Chicago official website]\n\n{{Hotels in Chicago}}\n{{Chicago Landmark skyscrapers}}\n\n[[Category:Hotel buildings completed in 1924]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper hotels in Chicago]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = November 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Redirect|Allerton Hotel|the New York City Hotel|Allerton Hotel for Women}}\n{{Infobox building\n|name               = Warwick Allerton - Chicago\n|image              = 20070513_Allerton_Hotel_and_Michigan_Ave_edit_cropped.jpg\n|image_size         = 300px\n|location           = 701 North [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]].<br/>[[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n|caption            = \n|coordinates        = {{coord|41.8952|-87.6238|region:US-IL|display=inline,title}}\n|status             = \n|start_date         = 1922\n|completion_date    = 1924\n|opening            = 1924\n|building_type      = hotel\n|antenna_spire      = \n|roof               = {{convert|360|ft|m}}\n|top_floor          = \n|floor_count        = 25\n|elevator_count     = \n|cost               = $4 million\n|floor_area         = \n|architect          = Murgatroyd & Ogden, with [[Fugard & Knapp]]\n|structural_engineer= \n|main_contractor    = \n|developer          = Allerton Hotels\n|owner              = [[Warwick International Hotels (WIH)|Warwick International Hotels]]\n|embedded           = {{Designation list|embed=yes|designation1=Chicago|designation1_date=May 29, 1998}}\n|references         = <ref>{{emporis|116862}}</ref>\n}}\n[[File:Allerton Tip Top Tap sign (15578891745).jpg|thumb|right|200px|'Tip Top Tap' sign]]\nThe '''Warwick Allerton - Chicago''' (formerly '''Allerton Hotel''' and '''Warwick Allerton Hotel Chicago''' and '''Allerton Crowne Plaza Hotel''') is a 25-story {{convert|360|ft|m|abbr=on}} hotel skyscraper on the [[Magnificent Mile]] in the [[Near North Side, Chicago|Near North Side]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]].<ref name=EMP>{{cite web| url=http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=allertoncrowneplaza-chicago-il-usa|accessdate=May 14, 2007| year=2007| title=Allerton Crowne Plaza| publisher=Emporis| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070429025629/http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=allertoncrowneplaza-chicago-il-usa| archivedate= April 29, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>   It was the first building in the city to feature pronounced setbacks and towers resulting from the 1923 zoning law.<ref name=\"EMP\" /><ref name=\"trib1\">{{cite press release| title=Chicago's Historic Allerton Hotel Rechristened an Independent Property| publisher=Oxford Lodging | date=February 5, 2007| accessdate=August 28, 2015| url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Chicago%27s+Historic+Allerton+Hotel+Rechristened+an+Independent...-a0158830052}}</ref> The building was designated a [[Chicago Landmark]] on May 29, 1998.<ref name=CL>{{cite web| url=http://webapps.cityofchicago.org/landmarksweb/web/landmarkdetails.htm?lanId=1237| title=Allerton Hotel| publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division| year=2003| accessdate=May 14, 2007}}</ref>\n\nWhen the Allerton Hotel first opened, it had fourteen floors of small apartment-style rooms for men and six similar floors for women, with a total of 1,000 rooms.  The hotel also boasted social events, gold, sports leagues, a library, solarium, and an in-house magazine.<ref name=\"trib2\">{{cite news| last=Conklin| first=Mike| title=75 Years Later, Allerton's Again in Tip Top Shape| work=[[Chicago Tribune]]| url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-05-21/features/9905210219_1_tap-new-owners-new-buildings| date=May 21, 1999}}</ref> An early resident was [[Louis Skidmore]], founder of the architectural firm [[Skidmore, Owings & Merrill]].\n\nIn the 1940s and 1950s, the hotel housed a swanky lounge on its top floor, called the \"Tip Top Tap\".  Although the lounge closed in 1961, the sign proclaiming its existence is still displayed on the building's exterior.<ref name=\"trib1\"/> By 1963, the room was home to a new restaurant, the Cloud Room, when [[Don McNeill (performer)|Don McNeill]] moved his broadcast of ''[[Don McNeill's Breakfast Club]]'' to the location. While the show was broadcast from the Allerton, McNeill's guests included regular [[Fran Allison]].<ref name=\"trib2\"/>\n\nAfter the Allerton Hotel was declared a Chicago landmark, it closed in August 1998 through May 1999 for a $40 million renovation.<ref name=\"trib2\" /><ref name=schmeltzer>{{cite news| title=Landmark Allerton Gets A Crowne| url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-03-26/business/9903260216_1_bass-hotels-resorts-historic-hotel-hotel-arm| last=Schmeltzer| first=John| date=March 26, 1999| work=Chicago Tribune| accessdate=August 28, 2015}}</ref> The firm of Eckenhoff Saunders Architects oversaw restoration work which restored the hotel's bygone grandeur and upgraded mechanical systems.<ref name=esa>{{cite web| title=Allerton Crowne Plaza Hotel| url=http://www.esadesign.com/portfolio/allerton/| publisher=Eckenhoff Saunders Architects| accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref>  When the hotel reopened as the Allerton Crowne Plaza Hotel, the twenty-third floor, which previously housed the Tip Top Tap and the Cloud Room, became the Renaissance Ballroom and a lounge opened on the second floor called Taps on Two featuring one of the Tip Top Tap's signature drinks, a [[Moscow mule]].<ref name=\"trib2\" />\n\nIn November 2006, a partnership of Oxford Lodging and Perry Capital purchased the hotel from FelCor Lodging for $70 million.<ref name=roeder>{{cite news| title=Allerton to get $10 mil. face-lift| url=http://charterslodging.com/PR_Articles/ChicagoSunTimes_Allerton.pdf| last=Roeder| first=David| work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]| date=November 10, 2006| accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref> The new owners ended the affiliation with Crowne Plaza and on February 2, 2007, the property was re-christened ''The Allerton Hotel''.  Shortly after the purchase, Oxford announced further renovations to the property.<ref name=\"trib1\"/>\n\nIn March 2014, [[Warwick International Hotels (WIH)|Warwick International Hotels]], a New York-based hotel chain, purchased the Allerton and renamed it the \"Warwick Allerton Hotel\".  Warwick acquired the Allerton from New York-based hedge fund manager Petra Capital Management LLC, which won a 2012-battle for control of the property in bankruptcy court.<ref name=diamond>{{cite press release| title=DiamondRock Hospitality Reaches Settlement on the Bankruptcy and Litigation Surrounding the Allerton Hotel in Chicago| url=http://www.hotel-online.com/News/PR2012_4th/Oct12_DiamondRockAllerton.html| date=October 31, 2012| accessdate=May 12, 2014| publisher=DiamondRock Hospitality}}</ref>  The new owners are planning renovations which may include reopening the Tip Top Tap on the hotel's 23rd floor.<ref name=hirst>{{cite news| url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-03-25/business/ct-chicago-hotels-allerton-0325-biz-20140325_1_hotel-rooms-radio-station-hotel-closing| title=New Allerton Hotel owner may return Tip Top Tap to its high point| accessdate=May 12, 2014| date=March 25, 2014| last=Hirst| first=Jean Ellen| work=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat-inline|The Allerton Hotel Chicago}}\n* [http://warwickhotels.com/allerton-hotel-chicago Warwick Allerton Hotel Chicago official website]\n\n{{Hotels in Chicago}}\n{{Chicago Landmark skyscrapers}}\n\n[[Category:Hotel buildings completed in 1924]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper hotels in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Chicago]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warwick_Allerton_-_Chicago"}
{"title_page": "Virgin Hotels Chicago", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox building\n|name               = Virgin Hotels Chicago\n| former_names        = Old Dearborn Bank Building\n| alternate_names     =203 North Wabash Avenue<br />54 East Lake Street\n|image              = 20150217 Virgin Hotels Chicago Wabash entry.JPG\n|image_size         = 300px\n|caption            = Virgin Hotels Chicago entrance\n|location           = 203 North Wabash, [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|41.8861|-87.6260|region:US-IL|display=inline,title}}\n|status             = Completed\n|start_date         = \n|est_completion     = \n|opening            = \n|building_type      = \n|antenna_spire      = \n|roof               = \n|top_floor          = \n|floor_count        = \n|elevator_count     = \n|cost               = \n|floor_area         = \n|architect          = [[Rapp and Rapp]] \n|ren_architect      = Booth Hansen \n|structural_engineer= \n|main_contractor    = \n|developer          = \n|owner              = [[Virgin Hotels]]\n|completion_date    = 1928\n|embedded           = {{Designation list|embed=yes|designation1=Chicago|designation1_date=June 4, 2003}}\n}}\nThe '''Virgin Hotels Chicago''' (formerly '''Old Dearborn Bank Building''' or '''203 North Wabash Avenue''') is a historic building in the [[Chicago Loop|Loop]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], that has been converted from use as an office building to use as a hotel run via a [[mobile app]] based business model. The 250-room hotel is the first of [[Richard Branson]]'s [[Virgin Hotels]] brand boutique hotels geared toward the female business traveller.\n\n==Old Dearborn Bank Building==\n[[File:20070530 203 North Wabash (2).JPG|Old Dearborn Bank Building in 2007 and the adjacent [[The Loop (CTA)|The Loop]] portion of the [[Chicago 'L']]|upright|thumb|left]]\nSituated at the intersection of East [[Lake Street (Chicago)|Lake Street]] and North Wabash Avenue,<ref name=VHAPoCP/> the Old Dearborn Bank Building was constructed between 1926 and 1928 with ornate medieval and mythological terra-cotta decoration that was typical of movie palaces that were its contemporaries. The [[neoclassical architecture]] designed building is one of only two [[Rapp and Rapp]] buildings designed as an [[office building]].<ref name=CL>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070509022043/http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/O/OldDearbornBank.html|archivedate=May 9, 2007|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/O/OldDearbornBank.html|title=Old Dearborn Bank Building|publisher=City of Chicago Dept. of Pl. and Devpmt., Landmarks Div.|year=2003|accessdate=May 21, 2007}}</ref><ref name=EMPORIS>{{cite web|url=http://www.emporis.com/building/203northwabash-chicago-il-usa|title=203 North Wabash|publisher=[[Emporis]]|accessdate=January 20, 2015}}</ref> Soon after the Old Dearborn Bank opened in 1928, it was acquired and its [[parent company]] was liquidated in the [[Great Depression in the United States|United States' Great Depression]].<ref name=VHCasrofbb/> The building, which is 27 stories high,<ref name=VhdBttoR&Rotih/> was designated a [[Chicago Landmark]] on June 4, 2003.<ref name=\"CL\" /> The {{convert|300|ft|m|1|adj=on}} light brown brick building with a steel structure includes 25 floors above ground and two below.<ref name=EMPORIS/>\n\nThe owners of the building defaulted on a $9 million loan from [[John Hancock Life Insurance]] resulting in the acquisition of the loan (and thus the property) for an undisclosed amount by Urban Street Properties LLC in April 2010. The building had been acquired by the previous owners for $9.5 million in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/realestate/20100407/CRED03/200037722/small-firm-snaps-up-east-loop-office-building|title=Small firm snaps up East Loop office building|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=April 7, 2010|work=[[Crain's Chicago Business]]|author=Gallun, Alby}}</ref>\n\n==Virgin Hotels Chicago==\nOn October 24, 2011, [[Virgin Hotels]], part of [[Virgin Group]], purchased the building with the aim of opening it as their first hotel in 2013 with approximately 250 rooms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2011-10-24/travel/chi-old-dearborn-bank-building-20111024_1_chicago-motor-club-building-chicago-developer-sam-roti-office-buildings |title=Virgin Hotels buys Old Dearborn Bank Building in East Loop |publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=October 24, 2011 |accessdate=May 6, 2013}}</ref> The transaction was an all-cash deal that was valued at about $14 million.<ref name=VHAPoCP/><ref name=VHoifhiCL>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/breaking/ct-virgin-hotel-chicago-biz-20150115-story.html|title=Virgin Hotels opens its first hotel in Chicago's Loop|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=January 16, 2015|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Briscoe, Tony}}</ref> The company hired The John Buck Company to renovate the building.<ref name=VhdBttoR&Rotih>{{cite web|url=http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/theskyline/2011/10/virgin-hotels-developer-buck-to-turn-old-rapp-rapp-office-tower-into-hotel-.html|title=Virgin hotels, developer Buck to turn old Rapp & Rapp office tower into hotel|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=October 24, 2011|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author= Cancino, Alejandra and Blair Kamin}}</ref><ref name=VHAPoCP>{{cite press release|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/10/24/idUS156789+24-Oct-2011+BW20111024|title=Virgin Hotels Announces Purchase of Chicago Property|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=October 24, 2011|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> The lead architect for the renovation was Booth Hansen.<ref name=VHCasrofbb/> The co-designers for the interior renovation were Rockwell Group Europe and Virgin Hotels' in-house design team.<ref name=EHFFICVHRBNPAaW>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-02-17/exactly-how-female-friendly-is-chicago-s-virgin-hotel-richard-branson-s-new-project-aimed-at-women-|title=Exactly How 'Female Friendly' Is Chicago\u2019s Virgin Hotel, Richard Branson\u2019s New Project Aimed at Women?|accessdate=April 21, 2015|date=February 17, 2015|author=Parker, Jennifer|work=[[Bloomberg Business]]}}</ref> The purchase was part of Virgin Hotels' 2010 business plan to acquire distressed properties in North America cheaply during the property downturn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304626304579507463175723476|title=Richard Branson's Virgin Hotels Are Slow to Launch: Entrepreneur Plans a Third U.S. Hotel, but First Is Unfinished|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|author=Karmin, Craig|accessdate=January 21, 2015|date=April 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{Multiple image\n<!-- Essential parameters -->\n | align =         right \n | direction =     vertical\n | background color = \n | header_background = \n | header_align =  <!-- center (default), left, right -->\n | header = \n | width =  250\n\n | image1 =  20150219 Virgin Hotels Chicago main bar2.JPG\n | width1 = \n | alt1 = \n | link1 = \n | caption1 = Commons Club main bar\n\n | image2 = 20150219 Virgin Hotels Chicago main desk.JPG\n | width2 = \n | alt2 = \n | link2 = \n | caption2 = Lobby main desk with check-in screens\n\n | footer_background = \n | footer_align =  <!-- left (default), center, right -->\n | footer = \n}}\nThe building opened for business as a hotel on January 15, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20150115/NEWS09/150119886/heres-what-virgins-female-friendly-chicago-hotel-looks-like|title=Here's what Virgin's 'female-friendly' Chicago hotel looks like|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=January 15, 2015|work==[[Crain's Chicago Business]]|author=Galland, Zoe}}</ref> It is the first of what was planned to be twenty [[Virgin Hotels]] locations that operate under this business model.<ref name=Ncdarkvmafdahh>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/travel/travel_news/article-2916596/Virgin-Hotels-rolls-red-carpet-debut-city-hotel-Chicago.html|title=No check-in desk, a room key vending machine and free drinks at happy hour: Sir Richard Branson launches Virgin's first city hotel|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=January 20, 2015|work=[[Daily Mail]]|author=Amey, Katie}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=October 2019}} The renovation took longer than planned due to the building's city landmark status, which required continuing coordination with the Commission on Chicago Landmarks. Original features that were retained include a 1920s oak cigar bar, brass elevator lobby doors and a tiled ceiling.<ref name=VHoifhiCL/> The final layout of 250 rooms includes 40 single-room suites and 2 penthouse suites.<ref name=VHoifhiCL/> 40 rooms are pet friendly.<ref name=VHoiCwahanL/>\n\nUnder the auspices of the Commission on Chicago Landmarks, the renovation included brick, window and steel frame replacement.<ref name=VHCasrofbb/> The focal point of the renovated building is the publicly accessible Commons Club on the second floor, with a contemporary-style bar, a full kitchen, a lounge area, curated books and local memorabilia. At the time of opening, four additional dining options were expected within three months.<ref name=VHoifhiCL/> The area was carved out of a former second-floor banking hall.<ref name=VHCasrofbb/>\n\n[[File:20150219 Virgin Hotels Chicago dog friendly door.JPG|thumb|left|upright|A pet friendly room with its sculptural marking]]\nThe hotel has no check-in desk; it uses a smartphone check-in system in which you scan a [[QR code]] and retrieve your room key from a vending machine.<ref name=Ncdarkvmafdahh/> The visitors use a mobile app, named Lucy, that the company describes as a \"personal comfort assistant\".<ref name=ML>{{cite web|url=http://virginhotels.com/about-the-app/|title=Meet Lucy: Your Personal Comfort Assistant|accessdate=January 20, 2015|publisher=[[Virgin Hotels]]}}</ref>  According to Mary Forgione of The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', the app can order more pillows, handle [[room service]] orders, and serve as a remote control for both the television and the hotel's music library.<ref name=VHoiCwahanL>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/deals/la-trb-virgin-hotels-opening-20150115-story.html|title=Virgin Hotels opens in Chicago, with a helpful app named Lucy|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=January 20, 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Forgione, Mary}}</ref> The website also suggests that the app can control room temperature, interface with the chat board, provide local knowledge, and coordinate your messages with hotel staff.<ref name=ML/>\n\nWhen asked about the operation, Virgin's [[Richard Branson]] said \"There won\u2019t be hidden charges, and you won\u2019t get charged $10 for a chocolate bar you know you can buy at a store for $2.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/18/travel/sir-richard-branson-enters-the-city-hotel-scene.html|title=Richard Branson Enters the City Hotel Scene |accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=January 13, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Earle-Levine, Julie}}</ref> Branson has stated that the brand is geared toward the female business traveler.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/richard-branson-pitches-virgin-hotels-as-female-friendly-1421172134|title=Richard Branson Pitches Virgin Hotels as Female-Friendly: First Property to Open in Chicago; Safety Features, Well-Lit Vanities Court Women|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=January 13, 2015|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|author=Karmin, Craig}}</ref> The rooms feature a patent-pending ergonomic bed and several female friendly features in the dressing room, shower and closets.<ref name=Ncdarkvmafdahh/>\n\n===Reviews===\n''[[Bloomberg Business]]'''s Jennifer Parker noted that the hotel was on the cutting edge of technology upon its opening, but questioned whether the hotel had any gender leanings. She found fault with the gym, toiletries, and delayed spa opening, but enjoyed the social ambiance, the normal retail prices of minibar items (rather than more standard hotel overpricing) and the top notch free [[Wi-Fi]]. She found many of the appealing elements of the designed to be dubiously marketed, but appealing nonetheless.<ref name=EHFFICVHRBNPAaW/>\n\n''[[Chicago Tribune]]'''s [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning architecture critic, [[Blair Kamin]], praised the incorporation of various wildlife into the decor and numerous elements of the rehab resulting from the alliance of real estate developers and historic preservationists, but made it clear that Virgin Hotels Chicago is not the [[Four Seasons Hotel Chicago]] or [[Ritz-Carlton Chicago (A Four Seasons Hotel)|Ritz-Carlton (Four Seasons)]]. He describes this as a successful recycling of a second-tier historic building.<ref name=VHCasrofbb>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/columnists/ct-virgin-hotel-kamin-met-0125-20150125-column.html|title=Virgin Hotel Chicago a stylish restoration of former bank building|accessdate=April 22, 2015|date=January 25, 2015|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Kamin, Blair}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Old Dearborn Bank Building 2007 Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:20070530 203 North Wabash.JPG\nImage:20070530 203 North Wabash (1).JPG\nImage:20070530 203 North Wabash (3).JPG\nImage:20070530 203 North Wabash (4).JPG\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Virgin Hotels Chicago}}\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{Virgin Group}}\n{{Hotels in Chicago}}\n{{Chicago Skyscrapers}}\n{{Chicago Landmark skyscrapers}}\n\n[[Category:Skyscraper hotels in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1928]]\n[[Category:Historic bank buildings in the United States]]\n[[Category:1928 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Chicago school architecture in Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox building\n|name               = Virgin Hotels Chicago\n| former_names        = Old Dearborn Bank Building\n| alternate_names     =203 North Wabash Avenue<br />54 East Lake Street\n|image              = 20150217 Virgin Hotels Chicago Wabash entry.JPG\n|image_size         = 300px\n|caption            = Virgin Hotels Chicago entrance\n|location           = 203 North Wabash, [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|41.8861|-87.6260|region:US-IL|display=inline,title}}\n|status             = Completed\n|start_date         = \n|est_completion     = \n|opening            = \n|building_type      = \n|antenna_spire      = \n|roof               = \n|top_floor          = \n|floor_count        = \n|elevator_count     = \n|cost               = \n|floor_area         = \n|architect          = [[Rapp and Rapp]] \n|ren_architect      = Booth Hansen \n|structural_engineer= \n|main_contractor    = \n|developer          = \n|owner              = [[Virgin Hotels]]\n|completion_date    = 1928\n|embedded           = {{Designation list|embed=yes|designation1=Chicago|designation1_date=June 4, 2003}}\n}}\nThe '''Virgin Hotels Chicago''' (formerly '''Old Dearborn Bank Building''' or '''203 North Wabash Avenue''') is a historic building in the [[Chicago Loop|Loop]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], that has been converted from use as an office building to use as a hotel run via a [[mobile app]] based business model. The 250-room hotel is the first of [[Richard Branson]]'s [[Virgin Hotels]] brand boutique hotels geared toward the female business traveller.\n\n==Old Dearborn Bank Building==\n[[File:20070530 203 North Wabash (2).JPG|Old Dearborn Bank Building in 2007 and the adjacent [[The Loop (CTA)|The Loop]] portion of the [[Chicago 'L']]|upright|thumb|left]]\nSituated at the intersection of East [[Lake Street (Chicago)|Lake Street]] and North Wabash Avenue,<ref name=VHAPoCP/> the Old Dearborn Bank Building was constructed between 1926 and 1928 with ornate medieval and mythological terra-cotta decoration that was typical of movie palaces that were its contemporaries. The [[neoclassical architecture]] designed building is one of only two [[Rapp and Rapp]] buildings designed as an [[office building]].<ref name=CL>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070509022043/http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/O/OldDearbornBank.html|archivedate=May 9, 2007|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/O/OldDearbornBank.html|title=Old Dearborn Bank Building|publisher=City of Chicago Dept. of Pl. and Devpmt., Landmarks Div.|year=2003|accessdate=May 21, 2007}}</ref><ref name=EMPORIS>{{cite web|url=http://www.emporis.com/building/203northwabash-chicago-il-usa|title=203 North Wabash|publisher=[[Emporis]]|accessdate=January 20, 2015}}</ref> Soon after the Old Dearborn Bank opened in 1928, it was acquired and its [[parent company]] was liquidated in the [[Great Depression in the United States|United States' Great Depression]].<ref name=VHCasrofbb/> The building, which is 27 stories high,<ref name=VhdBttoR&Rotih/> was designated a [[Chicago Landmark]] on June 4, 2003.<ref name=\"CL\" /> The {{convert|300|ft|m|1|adj=on}} light brown brick building with a steel structure includes 25 floors above ground and two below.<ref name=EMPORIS/>\n\nThe owners of the building defaulted on a $9 million loan from [[John Hancock Life Insurance]] resulting in the acquisition of the loan (and thus the property) for an undisclosed amount by Urban Street Properties LLC in April 2010. The building had been acquired by the previous owners for $9.5 million in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/realestate/20100407/CRED03/200037722/small-firm-snaps-up-east-loop-office-building|title=Small firm snaps up East Loop office building|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=April 7, 2010|work=[[Crain's Chicago Business]]|author=Gallun, Alby}}</ref>\n\n==Virgin Hotels Chicago==\nOn October 24, 2011, [[Virgin Hotels]], part of [[Virgin Group]], purchased the building with the aim of opening it as their first hotel in 2013 with approximately 250 rooms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2011-10-24/travel/chi-old-dearborn-bank-building-20111024_1_chicago-motor-club-building-chicago-developer-sam-roti-office-buildings |title=Virgin Hotels buys Old Dearborn Bank Building in East Loop |publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=October 24, 2011 |accessdate=May 6, 2013}}</ref> The transaction was an all-cash deal that was valued at about $14 million.<ref name=VHAPoCP/><ref name=VHoifhiCL>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/breaking/ct-virgin-hotel-chicago-biz-20150115-story.html|title=Virgin Hotels opens its first hotel in Chicago's Loop|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=January 16, 2015|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Briscoe, Tony}}</ref> The company hired The John Buck Company to renovate the building.<ref name=VhdBttoR&Rotih>{{cite web|url=http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/theskyline/2011/10/virgin-hotels-developer-buck-to-turn-old-rapp-rapp-office-tower-into-hotel-.html|title=Virgin hotels, developer Buck to turn old Rapp & Rapp office tower into hotel|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=October 24, 2011|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author= Cancino, Alejandra and Blair Kamin}}</ref><ref name=VHAPoCP>{{cite press release|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/10/24/idUS156789+24-Oct-2011+BW20111024|title=Virgin Hotels Announces Purchase of Chicago Property|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=October 24, 2011|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> The lead architect for the renovation was Booth Hansen.<ref name=VHCasrofbb/> The co-designers for the interior renovation were Rockwell Group Europe and Virgin Hotels' in-house design team.<ref name=EHFFICVHRBNPAaW>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-02-17/exactly-how-female-friendly-is-chicago-s-virgin-hotel-richard-branson-s-new-project-aimed-at-women-|title=Exactly How 'Female Friendly' Is Chicago\u2019s Virgin Hotel, Richard Branson\u2019s New Project Aimed at Women?|accessdate=April 21, 2015|date=February 17, 2015|author=Parker, Jennifer|work=[[Bloomberg Business]]}}</ref> The purchase was part of Virgin Hotels' 2010 business plan to acquire distressed properties in North America cheaply during the property downturn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304626304579507463175723476|title=Richard Branson's Virgin Hotels Are Slow to Launch: Entrepreneur Plans a Third U.S. Hotel, but First Is Unfinished|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|author=Karmin, Craig|accessdate=January 21, 2015|date=April 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{Multiple image\n<!-- Essential parameters -->\n | align =         right \n | direction =     vertical\n | background color = \n | header_background = \n | header_align =  <!-- center (default), left, right -->\n | header = \n | width =  250\n\n | image1 =  20150219 Virgin Hotels Chicago main bar2.JPG\n | width1 = \n | alt1 = \n | link1 = \n | caption1 = Commons Club main bar\n\n | image2 = 20150219 Virgin Hotels Chicago main desk.JPG\n | width2 = \n | alt2 = \n | link2 = \n | caption2 = Lobby main desk with check-in screens\n\n | footer_background = \n | footer_align =  <!-- left (default), center, right -->\n | footer = \n}}\nThe building opened for business as a hotel on January 15, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20150115/NEWS09/150119886/heres-what-virgins-female-friendly-chicago-hotel-looks-like|title=Here's what Virgin's 'female-friendly' Chicago hotel looks like|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=January 15, 2015|work==[[Crain's Chicago Business]]|author=Galland, Zoe}}</ref> It is the first of what was planned to be twenty [[Virgin Hotels]] locations that operate under this business model.<ref name=Ncdarkvmafdahh>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/travel/travel_news/article-2916596/Virgin-Hotels-rolls-red-carpet-debut-city-hotel-Chicago.html|title=No check-in desk, a room key vending machine and free drinks at happy hour: Sir Richard Branson launches Virgin's first city hotel|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=January 20, 2015|work=[[Daily Mail]]|author=Amey, Katie}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=October 2019}} The renovation took longer than planned due to the building's city landmark status, which required continuing coordination with the Commission on Chicago Landmarks. Original features that were retained include a 1920s oak cigar bar, brass elevator lobby doors and a tiled ceiling.<ref name=VHoifhiCL/> The final layout of 250 rooms includes 40 single-room suites and 2 penthouse suites.<ref name=VHoifhiCL/> 40 rooms are pet friendly.<ref name=VHoiCwahanL/>\n\nUnder the auspices of the Commission on Chicago Landmarks, the renovation included brick, window and steel frame replacement.<ref name=VHCasrofbb/> The focal point of the renovated building is the publicly accessible Commons Club on the second floor, with a contemporary-style bar, a full kitchen, a lounge area, curated books and local memorabilia. At the time of opening, four additional dining options were expected within three months.<ref name=VHoifhiCL/> The area was carved out of a former second-floor banking hall.<ref name=VHCasrofbb/>\n\n[[File:20150219 Virgin Hotels Chicago dog friendly door.JPG|thumb|left|upright|A pet friendly room with its sculptural marking]]\nThe hotel has no check-in desk; it uses a smartphone check-in system in which you scan a [[QR code]] and retrieve your room key from a vending machine.<ref name=Ncdarkvmafdahh/> The visitors use a mobile app, named Lucy, that the company describes as a \"personal comfort assistant\".<ref name=ML>{{cite web|url=http://virginhotels.com/about-the-app/|title=Meet Lucy: Your Personal Comfort Assistant|accessdate=January 20, 2015|publisher=[[Virgin Hotels]]}}</ref>  According to Mary Forgione of The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', the app can order more pillows, handle [[room service]] orders, and serve as a remote control for both the television and the hotel's music library.<ref name=VHoiCwahanL>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/deals/la-trb-virgin-hotels-opening-20150115-story.html|title=Virgin Hotels opens in Chicago, with a helpful app named Lucy|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=January 20, 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Forgione, Mary}}</ref> The website also suggests that the app can control room temperature, interface with the chat board, provide local knowledge, and coordinate your messages with hotel staff.<ref name=ML/>\n\nWhen asked about the operation, Virgin's [[Richard Branson]] said \"There won\u2019t be hidden charges, and you won\u2019t get charged $10 for a chocolate bar you know you can buy at a store for $2.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/18/travel/sir-richard-branson-enters-the-city-hotel-scene.html|title=Richard Branson Enters the City Hotel Scene |accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=January 13, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Earle-Levine, Julie}}</ref> Branson has stated that the brand is geared toward the female business traveler.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/richard-branson-pitches-virgin-hotels-as-female-friendly-1421172134|title=Richard Branson Pitches Virgin Hotels as Female-Friendly: First Property to Open in Chicago; Safety Features, Well-Lit Vanities Court Women|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=January 13, 2015|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|author=Karmin, Craig}}</ref> The rooms feature a patent-pending ergonomic bed and several female friendly features in the dressing room, shower and closets.<ref name=Ncdarkvmafdahh/>\n\n===Reviews===\n''[[Bloomberg Business]]'''s Jennifer Parker noted that the hotel was on the cutting edge of technology upon its opening, but questioned whether the hotel had any gender leanings. She found fault with the gym, toiletries, and delayed spa opening, but enjoyed the social ambiance, the normal retail prices of minibar items (rather than more standard hotel overpricing) and the top notch free [[Wi-Fi]]. She found many of the appealing elements of the designed to be dubiously marketed, but appealing nonetheless.<ref name=EHFFICVHRBNPAaW/>\n\n''[[Chicago Tribune]]'''s [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning architecture critic, [[Blair Kamin]], praised the incorporation of various wildlife into the decor and numerous elements of the rehab resulting from the alliance of real estate developers and historic preservationists, but made it clear that Virgin Hotels Chicago is not the [[Four Seasons Hotel Chicago]] or [[Ritz-Carlton Chicago (A Four Seasons Hotel)|Ritz-Carlton (Four Seasons)]]. He describes this as a successful recycling of a second-tier historic building.<ref name=VHCasrofbb>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/columnists/ct-virgin-hotel-kamin-met-0125-20150125-column.html|title=Virgin Hotel Chicago a stylish restoration of former bank building|accessdate=April 22, 2015|date=January 25, 2015|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Kamin, Blair}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Old Dearborn Bank Building 2007 Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:20070530 203 North Wabash.JPG\nImage:20070530 203 North Wabash (1).JPG\nImage:20070530 203 North Wabash (3).JPG\nImage:20070530 203 North Wabash (4).JPG\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Virgin Hotels Chicago}}\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{Virgin Group}}\n{{Hotels in Chicago}}\n{{Chicago Skyscrapers}}\n{{Chicago Landmark skyscrapers}}\n\n[[Category:Skyscraper hotels in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1928]]\n[[Category:Historic bank buildings in the United States]]\n[[Category:1928 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Chicago school architecture in Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virgin_Hotels_Chicago"}
{"title_page": "Arundel and South Downs (UK Parliament constituency)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{coord|51.856|-0.559|display=title|region:GB_scale:100000}}\n{{Infobox UK constituency main\n |name        = Arundel and South Downs\n |parliament  = uk\n |map1        = ArundelSouthDowns2007\n |map2        = EnglandWestSussex\n |map_entity  = West Sussex\n |map_year    = \n |year        = 1997\n |abolished   = \n |type        = County\n |previous    = [[Arundel (UK Parliament constituency)|Arundel]] and [[Horsham (UK Parliament constituency)|Horsham]]\n |next        = \n | population = 97,267 (2011 census)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6507707&c=&d=27&e=62&g=6430187&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=1&s=1422104706393&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2473|title=Usual Resident Population, 2011 |website=Neighbourhood Statistics |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=26 January 2015}}</ref>\n |electorate  = 76,697 (December 2010)<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.boundarycommissionforengland.org.uk/electoral-figures/electoral-figures.htm \n |title=Electorate Figures \u2013 Boundary Commission for England \n |date=4 March 2011 \n |work=2011 Electorate Figures \n |publisher=Boundary Commission for England \n |accessdate=13 March 2011 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101106204053/http://www.boundarycommissionforengland.org.uk/electoral-figures/electoral-figures.htm \n |archivedate=6 November 2010 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n |mp          = [[Andrew Griffith]]\n |party       = Conservative Party (UK)\n |region      = England\n |county      = West Sussex\n |european    = South East England\n |elects_howmany = One\n |towns = [[Arundel]], [[Hassocks]], [[Petworth]], [[Pulborough]] and [[Steyning]]\n}}\n\n'''Arundel and South Downs''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u00e6|r|\u1d7f|n|d|\u0259l}}) is a [[List of United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|constituency]]{{refn|A [[county constituency]] (for the purposes of election expenses and type of returning officer)|group= n}} created in 1997, represented in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]] since 2019 by [[Andrew Griffith]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].{{refn|As with all constituencies, the constituency elects one Member of Parliament (MP) by the [[first past the post]] system of election at least every five years.|group= n}}\n\n==Boundaries==\nThe constituency contains the town of [[Arundel]] and villages and [[hamlet (place)|hamlet]]s within the [[South Downs]] national park boundaries or encircled by the park, the largest of which are [[Hassocks]], [[Hurstpierpoint]], [[Petworth]], [[Pulborough]], [[Steyning]] ({{IPAc-en|s|t|\u025b|n|\u026a|\u014b}}) and Storrington.\n\n;2010 \u2013 reviewed boundaries adopted\nFollowing their [[Fifth Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies|review of parliamentary boundaries]] in West Sussex which Parliament approved in 2007, the [[Boundary Commission for England]] formed new constituencies.  First contested in 2010 the seat was constituted as follows:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Wards of the United Kingdom!! In district/borough of:\n|-\n| [[Angmering]], [[Arundel]], [[Barnham, West Sussex|Barnham]], [[Findon, West Sussex|Findon]], and [[Walberton]] ||[[Arun District|Arun]] \n|-\n| Bury, [[Petworth]], and Wisborough Green||[[Chichester (district)|Chichester]]\n|-\n| [[Bramber]], [[Upper Beeding]] and Woodmancote, Chanctonbury, Chantry, Cowfold,Partridge Green, Shermanbury and West Grinstead, [[Henfield]], Pulborough and Coldwaltham, and Steyning || [[Horsham (district)|Horsham]]\n|-\n|[[Hassocks]], and [[Hurstpierpoint]] and Downs.||[[Mid Sussex]]\n|}\n\nIn their recommendations, the Boundary Commission for England mooted the name ''Chanctonbury'' after uninhabited [[Chanctonbury Ring]], an ancient hill fort at its centre. This name was rejected during the local inquiry process at which the current name was chosen.<ref>Boundary Commission for England, fourth periodic report, 1995</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Results and EU referendum stance===\nThe 2017 result saw the sixth Conservative win.  \n\nSecond-place runners-up have been, listed in order, four times a Liberal Democrat, once the UKIP candidate and once the Labour candidate.  In line with regional trends, the highest percentage of the vote among these was the Liberal Democrat in 2010, with 27.9% of the vote.\n\nIn June 2016, an estimated [[Results_of_the_2016_United_Kingdom_European_Union_membership_referendum#List_of_constituency_results|50.3% of local adults voting in the EU membership referendum]] chose to remain in the European Union instead of to leave. This was defied in two January 2018 votes in Parliament by its MP, in line with his governing party's promise to adhere to the overall result of that referendum.<ref>https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/11377/nick_herbert/arundel_and_south_downs/divisions?policy=1065</ref> \n\nThe 2015-2017 status was as the 8th safest of the Conservative Party's 331 seats by percentage of majority.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukpolitical.info/conservative-mps-elected-2015.htm |title=List of Conservative MPs elected in 2015 by % majority |publisher=UK Political.info |accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===De-selection of incumbent seeking re-election in 2005===\nThe incumbent [[Howard Flight]] MP had national media coverage in the run-up to the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] due to his deselection requested by the party leader for membership of [[Conservative Way Forward]], lobbying for spending cuts to be more severe than set out in the small cuts in the 2005 manifesto. Flight hinted his preferred cuts would be as implemented by a Conservative government in his view.  He had represented the constituency since its creation at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]]. Anne Marie Morris, [[Laura Sandys]] and Nick Herbert put themselves forward for nomination as replacement candidates.  The chosen candidate, [[Nick Herbert]], won the seat at the election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsrss.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4407361.stm|title=BBC NEWS - UK - Politics - Tory shortlist to replace Flight|website=newsrss.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Morris and Sandys became MPs elsewhere in 2010.\n\n===Predecessor seats===\nThe seat and its predecessors have in the 20th century been a Conservative Party [[safe seat|stronghold]] save that the minor contributory Horsham seat to the area's electorate saw victory by 8.6% of the vote over the Labour Party in 1966, followed statistically by a next-most-marginal victory again with the Labour Party as runner-up, in 1950, of 14.4%.\n\nBetween 1974 and 1983, much of the South Downs area was part of the [[Shoreham (UK Parliament constituency)|Shoreham]] constituency, with the town of Arundel remaining in the Arundel constituency.\n\nPrior to 1974, the seat was largely part of the [[Arundel and Shoreham (UK Parliament constituency)|Arundel and Shoreham]] constituency.\n\n==Members of Parliament==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Election!!Member<ref name=\"rayment\">{{Rayment-hc|a|3|date=March 2012}}</ref>\n!Party\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\n| [[Howard Flight]]\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\n| [[Nick Herbert]]\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]\n| [[Andrew Griffith]]\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|}\n\n==Elections==\n[[File:Arundel and South Downs election graph.png|thumb|centre|750px|Arundel and South Downs election results]]\n===Elections in the 2010s===\n{{Election box begin | title = [[2019 United Kingdom general election|General election 2019]]: Arundel and South Downs<ref name =\"Statement of Persons Nominated\"><https://beta.horsham.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/76253/SPN-COMBINED-ASD-2019.pdf</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Andrew Griffith]]\n  |votes      = 35,566\n  |percentage = 57.9\n  |change     = -4.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party       = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n |candidate   = Alison Bennett\n |votes       = 13,045\n |percentage  = 21.2\n |change      = +13.3\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate  = Bella Sankey\n|votes      = 9,722\n|percentage = 15.8\n|change     = -6.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Green Party of England and Wales\n  |candidate  = Isabel Thurston\n  |votes      = 2,519\n  |percentage = 4.1\n  |change     = -0.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party = Independent (politician)\n|candidate = Robert Wheal\n|votes = 556\n|percentage = 0.9\n|change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n |votes = 22,521\n |percentage = 36.7\n |change = \u22122.9\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n |votes = 61,408\n |percentage = 75.1\n |change = -0.7\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n |winner = Conservative Party (UK)\n |swing = -8.9\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |title=[[2017 United Kingdom general election|General election 2017]]: Arundel and South Downs}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Nick Herbert]]\n  |votes      = 37,573\n  |percentage = 62.4\n  |change     = +1.6\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate  = Caroline Fife\n|votes      = 13,690\n|percentage = 22.7