{"title_page": "Victory Monument (Chicago)", "text_new": "{{other uses|Victory Monument (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n | name =Victory Sculpture\n | nrhp_type = cp | nocat = yes\n | designated_other1_name= Chicago Landmark\n | designated_other1_date= September 9, 1998\n | designated_other1_abbr= CL\n | designated_other1_link= Chicago Landmark\n | designated_other1_color= #aaccff\n | locmapin = United States Chicago\n| image =Victory Monument Chicago 2.jpg\n| caption = View facing north\n| location= 35th Street and King Drive<br>[[Chicago, IL]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|49|50.6|N|87|37|1.7|W|display=inline,title}}\n| area =\n| built =1927\n| architect= John A. Nyden\n| customarchitect_title= Sculptor\n| customarchitect= Leonard Crunelle\n| architecture=\n| added = April 30, 1986\n| mpsub=Black Metropolis TR\n| refnum=86001089 <ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}}\nErected in 1927, the '''Victory Monument''', created by sculptor [[Leonard Crunelle]], was built to honor the Eighth Regiment of the Illinois National Guard, an African-American unit that served in France during [[World War I]].<ref name=\"nris\"/> It is located in the [[Black Metropolis-Bronzeville District]] in the [[Douglas, Chicago|Douglas]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago, IL|Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. The structure was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on April 30, 1986.<ref name=\"nris\"/> It was designated a [[Chicago Landmark]] on September 9, 1998.<ref name=CL>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/V/Victory.html|title=Victory Monument (Chicago)|publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division|year=2003|accessdate=May 7, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070410125837/http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/V/Victory.html|archive-date=April 10, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> An annual [[Memorial Day]] ceremony is held at the monument.<ref name=CL/>\n\n== Description and history ==\nThe [[Smithsonian Institution]]\u2019s [[Archives of American Art]] describes the monument:\n::A white granite shaft topped with a bronze [[doughboy]] sculpture. On the monument's shaft are three bronze relief panels depicting life-sized figures. (Victory Panel:) Left full-length profile of a Classically draped African-American female figure representing motherhood. In her hand she holds a branch symbolizing Victory. (Columbia Panel:) Full-length Classically draped female figure with a helmet on her head. In her proper left hand she holds a tablet inscribed with the names of battles in which African-American soldiers fought. (African-American Soldier Panel:) A bare chested African-American soldier of the 370th Infantry, which fought in France, standing with an eagle in left profile in front of him.<ref name = \"siris\">{{Cite web\n| title = Victory, World War I Black Soldiers' Memorial, (sculpture).\n| work = Smithsonian Institution Research Information System\n| accessdate = February 9, 2014\n| url = http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=G29SO53129625.56452&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!8046~!36&ri=5&aspect=Browse&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Crunelle,+Leonard,+1872-1944,+sculptor.&index=AUTHOR&uindex=&aspect=Browse&menu=search&ri=5\n}}</ref>\n\n::In 1927, the State of Illinois erected this monument in the Chicago neighborhood known as \"[[Douglas, Chicago#Bronzeville|Bronzeville]],\" which was home of the \"Fighting Eighth\" Regiment of the [[Illinois National Guard]]. The names of 137 members of the [[370th Infantry Regiment (United States)|Eighth Infantry]], Illinois National Guard, who lost their lives during World War I, are inscribed on a bronze panel. The Eighth Regiment of the Illinois National Guard was reorganized as the [[370th Infantry Regiment (United States)|370th U.S. Infantry of the 93rd Division]], and this regiment saw service on WWI major battlefields. It was the last regiment pursuing the retreating German forces in the [[Aisne-Marne]] region of France, just before the November 11, 1918 Armistice. The doughboy on top of the shaft was added in 1936.<ref name = \"siris\" />\n\n[[File:Fountain Of The Great Lakes.jpg|thumb|left|''[[Fountain of the Great Lakes]]'' was almost located at 35th and King Drive; it is at the [[Art Institute of Chicago]].]]\nIn 1908 while [[Aaron Montgomery Ward]] was contesting the land use law for [[Grant Park (Chicago)|Grant Park]] for a second time in the [[Illinois Supreme Court]], the [[Art Institute of Chicago]] considered locating the ''[[Fountain of the Great Lakes]]'' at 35th Street and Grand Boulevard (the latter has been renamed as Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Drive.)<ref>{{cite book|title=Public Sculptor: Lorado Taft and the Beautification of Chicago|author=Garvey, Timothy J.|year=1988|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=0-252-01501-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/publicsculptorlo00garv/page/17 17]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/publicsculptorlo00garv/page/17}}</ref>  Instead, the Victory Monument was installed at this intersection.<ref name=CL/>\n\nThe [[Bud Billiken Parade]] has for many years traveled along King Drive. In some years, the Parade has started at 31st and King and in other years it has started as far south as 39th and King Drive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uchospitals.edu/programs/community/sponsorships/billiken.html|title=Bud Billiken Parade|accessdate=July 19, 2009|publisher=[[University of Chicago Medical Center]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.budbillikenparade.com/|title=Bud Billiken Parade & Picnic|accessdate=July 19, 2009}}</ref> It has often started very near this monument.\n\nRecently, the monument has received a grant for restoration as part of World War I centennial activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-wwi-centennial-met-20170927-story.html|title=For WWI centennial, six Illinois memorials to get restoration funds|first=Gregory|last=Pratt|publisher=|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=September 28, 2017|date=September 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\nThe monument features 4 bronze panels and a sculpture of a soldier atop that was added in 1936.<ref name=CL/>  To the north of the monument is a court with 4 plaques in the large [[tile|tilings]].  The plaques honor [[Robert Henry Lawrence, Jr.]], [[Truman Gibson, Sr.]]/[[Truman Gibson, Jr.]], [[Franklin A. Denison]], & [[George R. Giles]].  To the south of the monument is a flagpole that flies the [[United States flag]], [[Municipal Flag of Chicago]], [[POW/MIA flag]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery perrow=\"5\">\nImage:20070601 Victory Monument (3).JPG|Close up view facing south\nImage:20070601 Victory Monument (7).JPG|View facing south\nImage:20070601 Victory Monument (8).JPG|North walking court plaque\nImage:20070601 Victory Monument (9).JPG|Memorial plaque\nImage:20070601 Victory Monument.JPG|Monument and flagpole\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[370th Infantry Regiment (United States)]]\n* [[List of public art in Chicago]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{Cite book\n| pages = 214\u2013230\n| last = Scott\n| first = Emmett J\n| authorlink = Emmett J. Scott\n| title = Scott's Official History of The American Negro in the World War\n| chapter = Chapter XV. \"The Eighth Illinois\"\n| accessdate = February 9, 2014\n| chapterurl = https://archive.org/details/scottsofficialhi00scot\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.nps.gov/history/NR/twhp/wwwlps/lessons/53black/53black.htm ''Chicago's Black Metropolis: Understanding History Through a Historic Place,'' a National Park Service Teaching with Historic Places (TwHP) lesson plan]\n\n{{Registered Historic Places}}\n{{Chicago Landmark memorials and monuments}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1927]]\n[[Category:1927 sculptures]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Military monuments and memorials in the United States]]\n[[Category:Black people in art]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Historic district contributing properties in Illinois]]\n[[Category:African-American history in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials on the National Register of Historic Places in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Statues in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of men in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of women in Illinois]]\n[[Category:1927 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of African-Americans]]\n[[Category:African-American military monuments and memorials]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of birds in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{other uses|Victory Monument (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n | name =Victory Sculpture\n | nrhp_type = cp | nocat = yes\n | designated_other1_name= Chicago Landmark\n | designated_other1_date= September 9, 1998\n | designated_other1_abbr= CL\n | designated_other1_link= Chicago Landmark\n | designated_other1_color= #aaccff\n | locmapin = United States Chicago\n| image =Victory Monument Chicago 2.jpg\n| caption = View facing north\n| location= 35th Street and King Drive<br>[[Chicago, IL]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|49|50.6|N|87|37|1.7|W|display=inline,title}}\n| area =\n| built =1927\n| architect= John A. Nyden\n| customarchitect_title= Sculptor\n| customarchitect= Leonard Crunelle\n| architecture=\n| added = April 30, 1986\n| mpsub=Black Metropolis TR\n| refnum=86001089 <ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}}\nErected in 1927, the '''Victory Monument''', created by sculptor [[Leonard Crunelle]], was built to honor the Eighth Regiment of the Illinois National Guard, an African-American unit that served in France during [[World War I]].<ref name=\"nris\"/> It is located in the [[Black Metropolis-Bronzeville District]] in the [[Douglas, Chicago|Douglas]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago, IL|Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. The structure was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on April 30, 1986.<ref name=\"nris\"/> It was designated a [[Chicago Landmark]] on September 9, 1998.<ref name=CL>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/V/Victory.html|title=Victory Monument (Chicago)|publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division|year=2003|accessdate=May 7, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070410125837/http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/V/Victory.html|archive-date=April 10, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> An annual [[Memorial Day]] ceremony is held at the monument.<ref name=CL/>\n\n== Description and history ==\nThe [[Smithsonian Institution]]\u2019s [[Archives of American Art]] describes the monument:\n::A white granite shaft topped with a bronze [[doughboy]] sculpture. On the monument's shaft are three bronze relief panels depicting life-sized figures. (Victory Panel:) Left full-length profile of a Classically draped African-American female figure representing motherhood. In her hand she holds a branch symbolizing Victory. (Columbia Panel:) Full-length Classically draped female figure with a helmet on her head. In her proper left hand she holds a tablet inscribed with the names of battles in which African-American soldiers fought. (African-American Soldier Panel:) A bare chested African-American soldier of the 370th Infantry, which fought in France, standing with an eagle in left profile in front of him.<ref name = \"siris\">{{Cite web\n| title = Victory, World War I Black Soldiers' Memorial, (sculpture).\n| work = Smithsonian Institution Research Information System\n| accessdate = February 9, 2014\n| url = http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=G29SO53129625.56452&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!8046~!36&ri=5&aspect=Browse&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Crunelle,+Leonard,+1872-1944,+sculptor.&index=AUTHOR&uindex=&aspect=Browse&menu=search&ri=5\n}}</ref>\n\n::In 1927, the State of Illinois erected this monument in the Chicago neighborhood known as \"[[Douglas, Chicago#Bronzeville|Bronzeville]],\" which was home of the \"Fighting Eighth\" Regiment of the [[Illinois National Guard]]. The names of 137 members of the [[370th Infantry Regiment (United States)|Eighth Infantry]], Illinois National Guard, who lost their lives during World War I, are inscribed on a bronze panel. The Eighth Regiment of the Illinois National Guard was reorganized as the [[370th Infantry Regiment (United States)|370th U.S. Infantry of the 93rd Division]], and this regiment saw service on WWI major battlefields. It was the last regiment pursuing the retreating German forces in the [[Aisne-Marne]] region of France, just before the November 11, 1918 Armistice. The doughboy on top of the shaft was added in 1936.<ref name = \"siris\" />\n\n[[File:Fountain Of The Great Lakes.jpg|thumb|left|''[[Fountain of the Great Lakes]]'' was almost located at 35th and King Drive; it is at the [[Art Institute of Chicago]].]]\nIn 1908 while [[Aaron Montgomery Ward]] was contesting the land use law for [[Grant Park (Chicago)|Grant Park]] for a second time in the [[Illinois Supreme Court]], the [[Art Institute of Chicago]] considered locating the ''[[Fountain of the Great Lakes]]'' at 35th Street and Grand Boulevard (the latter has been renamed as Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Drive.)<ref>{{cite book|title=Public Sculptor: Lorado Taft and the Beautification of Chicago|author=Garvey, Timothy J.|year=1988|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=0-252-01501-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/publicsculptorlo00garv/page/17 17]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/publicsculptorlo00garv/page/17}}</ref>  Instead, the Victory Monument was installed at this intersection.<ref name=CL/>\n\nThe [[Bud Billiken Parade]] has for many years traveled along King Drive. In some years, the Parade has started at 31st and King and in other years it has started as far south as 39th and King Drive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uchospitals.edu/programs/community/sponsorships/billiken.html|title=Bud Billiken Parade|accessdate=July 19, 2009|publisher=[[University of Chicago Medical Center]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.budbillikenparade.com/|title=Bud Billiken Parade & Picnic|accessdate=July 19, 2009}}</ref> It has often started very near this monument.\n\nRecently, the monument has received a grant for restoration as part of World War I centennial activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-wwi-centennial-met-20170927-story.html|title=For WWI centennial, six Illinois memorials to get restoration funds|first=Gregory|last=Pratt|publisher=|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=September 28, 2017|date=September 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\nThe monument features 4 bronze panels and a sculpture of a soldier atop that was added in 1936.<ref name=CL/>  To the north of the monument is a court with 4 plaques in the large [[tile|tilings]].  The plaques honor [[Robert Henry Lawrence, Jr.]], [[Truman Gibson, Sr.]]/[[Truman Gibson, Jr.]], [[Franklin A. Denison]], & [[George R. Giles]].  To the south of the monument is a flagpole that flies the [[United States flag]], [[Municipal Flag of Chicago]], [[POW/MIA flag]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery perrow=\"5\">\nImage:20070601 Victory Monument (3).JPG|Close up view facing south\nImage:20070601 Victory Monument (7).JPG|View facing south\nImage:20070601 Victory Monument (8).JPG|North walking court plaque\nImage:20070601 Victory Monument (9).JPG|Memorial plaque\nImage:20070601 Victory Monument.JPG|Monument and flagpole\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[370th Infantry Regiment (United States)]]\n* [[List of public art in Chicago]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==